---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import BlogCrossLinks from '../../components/BlogCrossLinks.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Foreign Words Valid in Scrabble — Borrowed Gems That Score Big"
  description="Discover foreign loanwords legal in English Scrabble. From QI and TOFU to FJORD and KIBBUTZ — high-scoring borrowed words from 20+ languages."
  keywords="foreign words scrabble, loanwords scrabble, borrowed words valid scrabble, QI scrabble, TOFU scrabble, FJORD scrabble, PIZZA scrabble, foreign origin scrabble words, SOWPODS loanwords, scrabble word finder"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Foreign Words Valid in Scrabble — Borrowed Gems That Score Big",
    "description": "Discover foreign loanwords legal in English Scrabble. From QI and TOFU to FJORD and KIBBUTZ — high-scoring borrowed words from 20+ languages.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "dateModified": "2026-06-25",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/foreign-words-valid-in-scrabble" }
  })} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are foreign words allowed in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Words of foreign origin are valid if they appear in the official Scrabble dictionary (TWL or SOWPODS). Words like QI (Chinese), TOFU (Japanese), PIZZA (Italian), and FJORD (Norwegian) are all playable because they have been adopted into English." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What high-scoring foreign-origin words work in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "QI (11 pts), QOPH (18 pts), PIZZA (25 pts), FJORD (16 pts), KIBBUTZ (24 pts), and SCHMALTZ (24 pts) are high-scoring words borrowed from other languages that are valid in English Scrabble." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do foreign words enter the Scrabble dictionary?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A foreign word becomes valid when major English dictionaries (Merriam-Webster, Collins) include it as an adopted English word. Dictionary committees review new additions periodically, typically every few years." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is QI a foreign word?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes, QI comes from Chinese and refers to the life force or vital energy in traditional Chinese philosophy. It was added to the Official Scrabble Players Dictionary in 2006 and scores 11 points. It's the most-played Q-without-U word." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/dictionaries/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors text-gray-300">Dictionaries</a>
      </nav>

      <BlogCrossLinks title="Foreign Words Valid in Scrabble — Borrowed Gems That Score Big" />

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>7 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        English is a magpie language — it borrows shamelessly from every tongue it touches. And Scrabble players reap the benefits. Hundreds of words from Japanese, Arabic, Hindi, Yiddish, and Norwegian sit in the official dictionaries, many of them high-scoring thanks to uncommon letter combinations. Here's your guide to the best foreign loanwords that are perfectly legal on the Scrabble board.
      </p>

      <!-- Section 1: How Foreign Words Become Legal -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">How Foreign Words Become Legal in Scrabble</h2>

      <p>A word doesn't need to be "English" by birth to appear on a Scrabble board. It just needs to have been <span class="text-white font-medium">adopted into English</span> and included in one of the official dictionaries.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The Rule</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">A foreign word is valid in Scrabble if it appears in <span class="text-white font-medium">Merriam-Webster</span> (for TWL) or <span class="text-white font-medium">Collins English Dictionary</span> (for SOWPODS). Once adopted, it's treated identically to any native English word.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 The Adoption Path</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">A foreign word enters everyday English usage (e.g., "sushi" appears in newspapers, menus, conversation)</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Major dictionaries add it as an English headword (Merriam-Webster, Collins, Oxford)</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Scrabble dictionary committees include it in the next update (TWL updates every ~5 years, SOWPODS more frequently)</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">The word becomes playable in tournaments worldwide — no asterisk, no special rules</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2: Top Foreign Words by Language -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Best Foreign Loanwords by Language of Origin</h2>

      <p>These words come from languages all over the world. Many feature uncommon letter combinations (Q without U, double Z, FJ) that make them high-scoring staples in competitive play.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">20+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Source languages</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">500+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Loanwords in SOWPODS</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">PIZZA (highest common)</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">11 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">QI (most played)</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Points</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Origin</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Meaning</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Dict</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">QI</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">11</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Chinese</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Life force / vital energy</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">PIZZA</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">25</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Italian</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Flatbread with toppings</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">FJORD</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">16</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Norwegian</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Narrow sea inlet</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">KIBBUTZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">24</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Hebrew</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Communal settlement</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">SCHMALTZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">24</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Yiddish</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Excessive sentimentality</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">TOFU</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">7</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Japanese</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Soybean curd</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">KARMA</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">11</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Sanskrit</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Destiny from past actions</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">QOPH</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">18</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Hebrew</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">19th Hebrew letter</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">ZEITGEIST</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">19</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">German</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Spirit of the age</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">SOWPODS</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">MANGA</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">8</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Japanese</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Japanese comic art</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">SOWPODS</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">GURU</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">5</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Hindi/Sanskrit</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Spiritual teacher</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-bold">CHUTZPAH</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-semibold">27</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-purple-300">Yiddish</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Shameless audacity</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">Both</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 3: Language Clusters -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Language Clusters — Where the Best Words Come From</h2>

      <p>Some languages contribute disproportionately to the Scrabble dictionary. Yiddish, Japanese, and Arabic are goldmines for unusual letter combinations that score well.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🇯🇵 Japanese</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">TOFU, SAKE, SUMO, EMOJI, MANGA, RAMEN, TSUNAMI, KARATE, JUDO, ANIME, BONSAI, ORIGAMI, WASABI, SHOGUN</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🇮🇱 Hebrew / Yiddish</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">KIBBUTZ, SCHMALTZ, CHUTZPAH, QOPH, KVETCH, SCHMUCK, MENSCH, KLUTZ, SHMOOZE, GOLEM, BAGEL, NOSH</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🇮🇳 Hindi / Sanskrit / Urdu</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">KARMA, GURU, YOGA, JUNGLE, THUG, AVATAR, NIRVANA, MANTRA, SHAMPOO, VERANDA, PAJAMA, BUNGALOW</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🇸🇦 Arabic</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">QADI, QANAT, WADI, HAREM, ALGEBRA, ZERO, ZENITH, NADIR, ASSASSIN, COFFEE, COTTON, SAFARI</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🇩🇪 German</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">ZEITGEIST, KINDERGARTEN, WANDERLUST, ANGST, POLTERGEIST, DOPPELGANGER, KITSCH, UBER, STRUDEL</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🇮🇹 Italian</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">PIZZA, PIAZZA, MOTTO, GRAFFITI, STUDIO, CASINO, VOLCANO, FIASCO, REPLICA, DIVA, ARIA, SOLO</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/scrabble-dictionaries-languages-weird-words/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Scrabble Dictionaries & Weird Words — why TWL and SOWPODS differ</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/official-scrabble-dictionary-guide/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Official Scrabble Dictionary Guide — which words are valid where</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 4: High-Scoring Strategy -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategic Value — Why Loanwords Win Games</h2>

      <p>Foreign loanwords aren't just novelties — many are strategically essential because they use difficult letters (Q, Z, X, J, K) in ways native English words don't.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Q without U lifeline:</span> QI, QOPH, QADI, QAID, QANAT, QAT — all from Arabic/Hebrew/Chinese. Without these loanwords, drawing a Q with no U would be catastrophic.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Double-Z jackpots:</span> PIZZA (25), PIAZZA (26), PIZZAZZ (45 in theory) — Italian gives us the only common double-Z words in the dictionary.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Consonant-heavy clusters:</span> FJORD, SCHMALTZ, KVETCH, SCHMUCK — Norwegian, Yiddish, and German give us consonant-dense words that work when your rack is vowel-starved.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Short words for tight spots:</span> QI (2), ZA (2), KA (2), GO (2) — these 2-letter loanwords are lifelines for parallel plays and squeezing into tight board positions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 MVP Loanword</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">QI</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">11 points • Chinese • 2 letters • Q without U</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">The single most important loanword in competitive Scrabble. Before QI was added in 2006, drawing a Q without a U was essentially losing 10 points. Now it's a scoring opportunity — especially on a triple-letter square (31 points) or as a parallel play alongside existing words.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 5: Recently Added Loanwords -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Recently Added — Modern Loanwords</h2>

      <p>The Scrabble dictionary isn't static. Modern cultural exchange keeps adding new foreign words. Here are some of the more recent additions that competitive players have quickly adopted.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">EMOJI</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Japanese</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">RAMEN</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Japanese</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">QUINOA</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Quechua</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">WASABI</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Japanese</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">FALAFEL</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Arabic</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">BOKEH</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Japanese</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">UMAMI</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Japanese</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">HIJAB</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">Arabic</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-green-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">✓ Pro Tip</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Japanese is the single biggest source of modern loanwords entering the Scrabble dictionary. Food words (RAMEN, WASABI, UMAMI, EDAMAME), cultural terms (MANGA, ANIME, EMOJI), and martial arts (KARATE, JUDO, AIKIDO) all score well thanks to their vowel-rich structures.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 6: TWL vs SOWPODS Differences -->
      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">TWL vs SOWPODS — Which Loanwords Are Where?</h2>

      <p>Not all loanwords are valid in both dictionaries. SOWPODS (international) is more permissive than TWL (North America). Some words you can play in London but not New York.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Valid in Both (TWL + SOWPODS)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">QI, PIZZA, FJORD, TOFU, KARMA, GURU, KIBBUTZ, CHUTZPAH, KARATE, TSUNAMI, AVATAR, BONSAI, ORIGAMI</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ SOWPODS Only (not TWL)</p>
